AB  - As with every new medium, from the production of print cartoons to computer games, the Internet is frequently seen as causal of harm. News about the Net features regularly in the mainstream media of newspapers and television, very often negatively associated with crime and harm. Such concerns evolved as the Internet spread. Once commercialised in the early 1990s, fears about its potential for crime, deviance and harm grew as rapidly as the new cyber-communications systems themselves. Alongside such fears, calls for censorship, control and monitoring led to a whole range of interventions by states, police, service providers, business, lobby groups and vigilantes. This chapter considers whether such calls for control should take precedence over the freedom of expression that has characterised the 'consensual hallucination' of cyberspace since its creation. This chapter will consider whether any lethal potential of cyberspace should take precedence over the importance of freedom of expression for truth, democracy and individual autonomy. The focus therefore is evidence of suicide and homicide where media accounts clearly attribute blame on cyberspace for extreme, actual identifiable harm and whether such cases justify the censorship of communications' freedom. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)
